<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ericameria palmeri </i>is a small shrub to 1.5 m high with ascending resinous stems and clustered, glandular, linear leaves. The composite heads contain a few yellow disk and ray flowers. The more common <i>E. palmeri </i>var. <i>pachylepis </i>grows in the Southern California Coast (261Bj, Bj), lower subsections of the Southern California Mountains and Valleys (M262Bk, Bn, Bp), the western Colorado Desert (322Cb), and northernmost Baja California. The rare <i>E. palmeri </i>var. <i>palmeri </i>is a CNPS list 2.2B plant in San Diego Co. <br/>
<br/>
The ecology of <i>E. palmeri </i>appears similar to that of the <i>Hazardia squarrosa </i>and <i>Isocoma menziesii</i> alliances. The stands occur in a larger matrix of annual grasslands. The pattern implies that this alliance is an early-seral shrub phase following shifts in management. Keeley (2001) considered annual grasslands along central and southern California coastlines to be fire induced. Once shrublands, these herbaceous landscapes largely created by Native Americans’ burning are currently maintained by fire and livestock grazing. In recent decades, woody vegetation including <i>E. palmeri </i>may be reestablishing with less fire and grazing. </div>
</div>

	
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Observations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Stands sampled near Lake Mathews in the Perris Valley and Hills (M262Bk) subsection (Klein and Evens 2005), and others observed in the Santa Rosa Plateau area (M262bf ) suggest this alliance. Further sampling and analysis will determine relationships and patterns of this alliance with related grasslands and coastal scrub vegetation in California. </div>
</div>

	

    
